</p><textarea readonly="" accesskey="," id="wpTextbox1" cols="80" rows="25" style="" lang="en" dir="ltr" name="wpTextbox1">{{DISPLAYTITLE:mEADL GSoC Proposal 1}}
=Introduction=

The specific task that we are looking to accomplish this summer is to enable seamless access to Android through the 4-way joystick interface that wheelchair users employ to maneuver around. An Arduino BT reads joystick data from the ECU of the wheelchair and sends it to the app on the Android. The Android app features a configurable menu structure keeping the possible inputs from the joystick in mind and enabling access to the available intents.

=Architecture=

Broadly the system can be separated into the following components:

# Read and transmit data from the wheelchair. 
# An Interface to show configurable actions on the Android and accordingly configure the menu. 
# Daemon on the Android to receive data from the wheelchair. 
# Execution of user selected menu option.

=Application Walk through=

# User downloads and installs the 'mEADL App'.
# App started.
# App scans for installed applications.[1] 
# A template/menu structure is provided with the available intents (actions) 
# User can edit this menu structure to their convenience. 
# The menu is setup. 
# App is turned to active mode. 
# User starts using the Joystick. 
# The controls are as shown in Fig.1 
# As the user browses the menu, the current selection is spoken out by the app. 
# User selects the category eg. Call. 
# In the Sub-menu, user selects the action eg. Make a call. 
# At any point the user may go back or exit by using the Back motion of the joystick. 
 
Note: If [1] is not possible, since the apps which have open intents are already known - a list can be provided to check the installed apps among them.

=Control Mechanism=

We have with us the following four controls on the wheelchair- UP, DOWN, RIGHT and LEFT. A circular menu system is proposed as detailed in Fig.1, where the RIGHT and the LEFT controls are used for browsing through the circular menu structure at that level. The UP control is used to select the option or to enter the sub-level. The DOWN control is used to cancel the action or go back one level. 

If the DOWN button is held for 10 seconds, the mEADL application exits. Long presses (>5sec) can be intelligently used to facilitate shortcuts.

=Software Components=

This section briefly outlines the software architecture.
 
==1. WebUI==
For the sake of portability onto other platforms and universality of the GUI it is proposed that user interface takes form of a local interactive web page. By appropriate use of jQuery we would be able to achieve a very easy to use and graphically engaging experience for the user. The WebUI gets a list of available applications and their intents from the Core-App (Refer pt.2 below) in the form of an XML file (Refer pt.3 below) and it presents these options to the user. 
 
A standard menu structure is created with the following hierarchy- 
&lt;br />a. The 1st level menu is formed with the intent-categories or apps. Eg. Music Player, Camera, Call 
&lt;br />b. The 2nd level menu lists down the available intents in that category. Eg. Playlist, Player, Controls etc for level-1 category of Music Player. 
&lt;br />c. The 3rd level deals with specific controls associated with the intent. Eg. For Making a call, the user interface shows the number pad.

The above menu structure can be rearranged at a particular level. Eg. More accessed categories like Call, Games can be placed closer to the starting point. 
 
The WebUI outputs a config.xml file which lists the menu structure.
 
==2. Core-App==
The Core-App is the platform specific part of the application. Here we outline the three basic components of the app-
 
====a. Scan for Apps====
An installed application profiler which is an integral part of the app. In the event this polling facility is not available for apps, and hence if we aren't able to scan for the available apps - we list down the apps from the supported available intents (See VI below) and ask the user to check the installed ones. Download links are provided for the non-installed apps.
 
===b. Intent Library===
The list of available open intents is well documented (below in VI.), this part of the Core-App acts like a database for the Intent URI and Actions associated to invoke the intents. The data is maintained in an XML file (intents.xml)- hence facilitating easy updates to the intent library.
 
===c. Daemon===
The daemon is the active process of the Core-App. It reads input from the Arduino BT board, renders the graphical menu by reading from the config.xml file (This file is outputted by the WebUI, the file contains the menu structure), on selecting an action - it refers to the intents.xml file for the details on invoking the Intent URI.

===d. On Screen Keyboard===
For various applications such as to make a call or to search the map, we require a facility to enter alphanumeric data. One way of doing this is selecting input data from an on screen keyboard using the joystick controls, although this method doesn't require any learning, the interaction steps to reach the goal increase drastically. An alternate approach would be to input using Morse code, this however requires training to achieve a decent input speed. Both the approaches mentioned above aren't ideal and have their own set of disadvantages. The formulation of an active strategy for data input remains an interesting challenge worth pursuing.

The brainstorming section for the on-screen keyboard is under the 'Text Input' heading above.

==3. Talk between WebUI &lt;> App==

The above listed three components of the Core-App talk to each other through XML files. The WebUI creates a config.xml which contains the menu structure. The list of available open intents are maintained in the intent.xml file.

=Available Intents=

*The current list of open available intents is maintained at - http://www.openintents.org/en/intentstable 
*The list of available application which support these open intents is maintained at - http://www.openintents.org/en/download 
*The intents provided by Google are documented here - http://developer.android.com/guide/appendix/g-app-intents.html 
*The libraries that can be invoked through intents are listed here - http://www.openintents.org/en/libraries

=Explorations=

This section documents other alternative tracks open for explorations. Some of the features from the below list maybe included with the app.

'''A. Eyes Free Shell'''
&lt;br />This is an accessibility app deployed by T.V.Raman and team which helps the blind use the Android by invoking the Eyes-Free shell and enabling app launch by speech commands. An insight into the code could prove useful in exploring alternative tracks for implementation.

'''B. Plugins - co-ordinate way''' 
&lt;br />The current intent based implementation is limited to the open intents that are available, it however cannot be extended to any and every app out there. This is an alternate approach based on programatically navigating the apps based on a common knowledge of user interface element's co-ordinates. The challenges however are - 1. The capacity to simulate a click based on a given co-ordinate information. 2. The ability to know the current interface on the user screen. 

Both of the above open security loopholes if not implemented properly.

'''C. Mapping joystick''' 
&lt;br />An ad-hoc hardware solution is to map the wheelchair joystick onto the Android's trackball. This solution requires a custom modded deploy of the Android. Also since most of the wheelchair joysticks have only four controls, navigating the user interface becomes cumbersome.

'''Note: '''B and C are not intended for deployement due to their 'hacky' nature. They are presented here for pure documenting / alternate track inspirational purposes.


=Timeline, Resources and Tools=

Detailed schedule TBD

*Our active code repository would be maintained here: [https://launchpad.net/meadl Launchpad - mEADL]
*Brainstorming, updates and discussions would happen here at the wiki.

